This folder contains all data needed to run our analyses, except RNA expression count matrices, which will be added here upon publication of the paper.

Due to file size limitations on GitHub, the RNA count matrix is divided into 18 files, with each file containing 100 samples (except the 18th file, which contains 115 samples). Of the 1815 samples, only 376 samples were analyzed in our paper, though the remaining 1439 were utilized when correcting the RNA counts for technical variables. If using the data, we suggest that you combine the 18 files into one excel spreadsheet.

The top row of the RNA count matrices contain 6 digit barcodes, which correspond to each blood sample. In R, open the file BarcodesOfOutcomeGroups.RData, which shows which barcodes belong to each group. In BarcodesOfOutcomeGroups.RData, all barcodes are for cord blood samples, and each barcode corresponds to a different child. The following are the groups contained in BarcodesOfOutcomeGroups.RData (not that some of these groups overlap - i.e. there are barcodes that fit into more than one of these groupings):
BarcodesOfTB: Cord blood samples of children who were diagnosed with TB disease before their 11th birthdays. (4 of these children received isoniazid prophylaxis before symptoms emerged yet they contracted TB disease anyway).
BarcodesOfNonInfected: Cord blood samples of children who were never diagnosed with TB disease and never had a postive TST before their 11th birthdays. None of these children received prophylaxis.
BarcodesOfAINoIsoniazid: Cord blood samples of children who had positive TSTs before their 11th birthdays but did not progress to TB disease. (AI stands for asymptomatic infected). None of these children received prophylaxis. 
BarcodesOfInfectedOrTB: Cord blood samples of children who had positive TSTs or TB diagnoses before their 11th birthdays. (Some of these children received isoniazid prophylaxis upon a positive TST test. To see which of these children were TST-positive non-progressors who did not receive prophylaxis, refer to BarcodesOfAINoIsoniazid above).
BarcodesOfNonDisease: Samples of children who were never diagnosed with TB disease before their 11th birthdays. (This incudes children who never had a positive TST and children with a postive TST but did not contract TB disease). None of these children received prophylaxis. 


In R, open AgesOfTSTConversionAndTBDiagnosis.RData to see the ages at which children were diagnosed with TB disease (see the object AgesOfTBDiagnosisDF). See the object AgeOfTSTConversionDF to see the ages at which children TST converted (note that if the age says 0, it indicates the child never TST converted) Note that we analyzed 376 children in our study, but there are 389 children in AgeOfTSTConversionDF - these additional 13 children received prophylaxis prior to having positive TSTs, so we excluded them from our study.

The other files in this folder contain the demographic/clinical covariates or technical covariates. For example, Batches.csv shows which Extraction, Library and Sequencing batches each sample was processed in during RNA sequencing.

Some files indicate "pids" for samples. The pids are identifiers for each individual. This is different from the sample barcodes because some individuals have multiple samples, so multiple barcodes correspond to one pid. However, as we only studied the cord blood samples in this paper, we only are interested in one barcode (the cord blood sample) for each pid.
